Definition 5.2. An uncountable limit cardinal $\kappa$ is almost strongly compact if for every $\mu<\kappa$, every $\kappa$-complete filter extends to a $\mu$-complete ultrafilter.
Definition 2.8. Fix infinite cardinals $\lambda\geq\mu$. Let $\Phi$ be a set of formulas in $L_{\lambda,\mu}$. Let $(\operatorname{\mathcal{K}},\leq_{\operatorname{\mathcal{K}}})$ be an abstract class. Define $\operatorname{\mathcal{K}}_{\Phi}:=(\operatorname{\mathcal{K}},\leq_{% \operatorname{\mathcal{K}}_{\Phi}})$ by $M\leq_{\operatorname{\mathcal{K}}_{\Phi}}N$ if and only if $M\leq_{\operatorname{\mathcal{K}}}N$ and $M\preceq_{\Phi}N$.
Definition 2.2. Suppose $\langle\operatorname{\mathcal{K}},\leq_{\operatorname{\mathcal{K}}}\rangle$ is a $\mu$-abstract class, with $\mu$ a regular cardinal. We say that $\langle\operatorname{\mathcal{K}},\leq_{\operatorname{\mathcal{K}}}\rangle$ is a $\mu$-abstract elementary class if the following properties hold: (1) (Coherence) if $M_{0},M_{1},M_{2}\in\operatorname{\mathcal{K}}$ with $M_{0}\leq_{\operatorname{\mathcal{K}}}M_{2}$, $M_{1}\leq_{\operatorname{\mathcal{K}}}M_{2}$, and $M_{0}\subseteq M_{1}$, then $M_{0}\leq_{\operatorname{\mathcal{K}}}M_{1}$; (2) (Tarski-Vaught chain axioms) If $\{M_{i}\in\operatorname{\mathcal{K}}:i\in I\}$ is a $\mu$-directed system, then: (a) $\bigcup_{i\in I}M_{i}\in\operatorname{\mathcal{K}}$ and, for all $j\in I$, we have $M_{j}\leq_{\operatorname{\mathcal{K}}}\bigcup_{i\in I}M_{i}$; and (b) if there is some $N\in\operatorname{\mathcal{K}}$ so that, for all $i\in I$, we have $M_{i}\leq_{\operatorname{\mathcal{K}}}N$, then we also have $\bigcup_{i\in I}M_{i}\leq_{\operatorname{\mathcal{K}}}N$. (3) (Löwenheim-Skolem-Tarski number axiom) There exists a cardinal $\lambda=\lambda^{<\mu}\geq|\operatorname{L}(\operatorname{\mathcal{K}})|+\mu$ such that for any $M\in\operatorname{\mathcal{K}}$ and $A\subseteq|M|$, there is some $N\leq_{\operatorname{\mathcal{K}}}M$ such that $A\subseteq|N|$ and $\|N\|\leq|A|^{<\mu}+\lambda$. $\operatorname{LS}(\operatorname{\mathcal{K}})$ is the minimal cardinal $\lambda$ with this property.1Note that $\operatorname{LS}(\operatorname{\mathcal{K}})$ really depends on $\mu$ but $\mu$ will always be clear from context.
Definition 4.7. We say that categories $\mathcal{C}$ and $\mathcal{D}$ are equivalent if the following equivalent conditions (see [Mac71] V.4.1) hold: (1) There is a functor $F:\mathcal{C}\to\mathcal{D}$ that is • full: For any $C_{1},C_{2}$ in $\mathcal{C}$, the map $f\mapsto F(f)$ is a surjection from $\operatorname{Hom}_{\mathcal{C}}(C_{1},C_{2})$ to $\operatorname{Hom}_{\mathcal{D}}(FC_{1},FC_{2})$. • faithful: For any $C_{1},C_{2}$ in $\mathcal{C}$, the map $f\mapsto F(f)$ is an injection from $\operatorname{Hom}_{\mathcal{C}}(C_{1},C_{2})$ to $\operatorname{Hom}_{\mathcal{D}}(FC_{1},FC_{2})$. • essentially surjective: Any object $D$ in $\mathcal{D}$ is isomorphic to $F(C)$ for some $C$ in $\mathcal{C}$. (2) There are functors $F:\mathcal{C}\to\mathcal{D}$ and $G:\mathcal{D}\to\mathcal{C}$ such that the compositions $FG$ and $GF$ are naturally isomorphic to the identity functors on $\mathcal{D}$ and $\mathcal{C}$, respectively.
Definition 6.9. Let $\mu\leq\lambda$ be regular cardinals. $C\subseteq\lambda$ is a $\mu$-club if it is unbounded and whenever $\langle\alpha_{i}:i<\delta\rangle$ is increasing in $C$ with $\mu\leq\text{cf }{\delta}<\lambda$, then $\sup_{i<\delta}\alpha_{i}\in C$.
Definition 5.1 (Definitions 3.1 and 3.3 in [Bon14]). Let $\operatorname{\mathcal{K}}$ be an abstract class and let $\kappa$ be an infinite cardinal. (1) $\operatorname{\mathcal{K}}$ is $(<\kappa)$-tame if for any distinct $p,q\in\text{gS}(M)$, there exists $A\subseteq|M|$ such that $|A|<\kappa$ and4We use here Galois types over sets as defined in [Vasb, Definition 2.16]. $p\upharpoonright A\neq q\upharpoonright A$. (2) $\operatorname{\mathcal{K}}$ is fully $(<\kappa)$-tame and short if for any distinct $p,q\in\text{gS}^{\alpha}(M)$, there exists $I\subseteq\alpha$ and $A\subseteq|M|$ such that $|I|+|A|<\kappa$ and $p^{I}\upharpoonright A\neq q^{I}\upharpoonright A$. (3) We say $\operatorname{\mathcal{K}}$ is tame if it is $(<\kappa)$-tame for some $\kappa$, similarly for fully tame and short.
