Definition 1.2.1. A classical t-structure $\bigl{(}\mathcal{T}^{\leqslant 0},\mathcal{T}^{\geqslant 0}\bigr{)}$ on $\mathcal{T}$ is a pair of strictly full subcategories of $\mathcal{T}$ such that, setting $\mathcal{T}^{\leqslant n}\mathbin{:=}\mathcal{T}^{\leqslant 0}[-n],\quad% \mathcal{T}^{\geqslant n}\mathbin{:=}\mathcal{T}^{\geqslant 0}[-n]$ for $n\in\mathbb{Z}$, one has: (a) $\mathcal{T}^{\leqslant 0}\subset\mathcal{T}^{\leqslant 1}$ and $\mathcal{T}^{\geqslant 1}\subset\mathcal{T}^{\geqslant 0}$; (b) $\mathrm{Hom}_{\raise 6.45pt\hbox to 1.0pt{}\mathcal{T}}(\mathcal{T}^{\leqslant 0% },\mathcal{T}^{\geqslant 1})=0$; (c) for any $X\in\mathcal{T}$, there exists a distinguished triangle $X_{\leqslant 0}\xrightarrow{}X\xrightarrow{}X_{\geqslant 1}\xrightarrow[]{% \mspace{10.0mu }{+1}\mspace{10.0mu }}$ in $\mathcal{T}$ with $X_{\leqslant 0}\in\mathcal{T}^{\leqslant 0}$ and $X_{\geqslant 1}\in\mathcal{T}^{\geqslant 1}$.
Definition 2.3.6. A subset $S$ of a bordered space ${\mathsf{M}}=({M},{\accentset{\vee}{M}})$ is a subset of $M$. We say that $S$ is open (resp. closed, locally closed) if it is so in ${M}$. We say that $S$ is relatively compact if it is contained in a compact subset of ${\accentset{\vee}{M}}$.
Definition 3.3.20. For $p\colon\mathbb{Z}_{\geqslant 0}\xrightarrow{}\mathbb{R}$ a perversity and $d\in\mathbb{Z}_{\geqslant 0}$, the shifted perversity $p[d]$ is given by $p[d](n)=p(d+n).$
Definition 3.1.1. (i) A subanalytic bordered space ${\mathsf{M}}=({M},{\accentset{\vee}{M}})$ is a bordered space such that ${\accentset{\vee}{M}}$ is a subanalytic space and ${M}$ is an open subanalytic subset of ${\accentset{\vee}{M}}$. (ii) A morphism $f\colon{\mathsf{M}}\xrightarrow{}{\mathsf{N}}=({N},{\accentset{\vee}{N}})$ of subanalytic bordered spaces is a morphism $f\colon{M}\xrightarrow{}{N}$ of subanalytic spaces such that its graph $\Gamma_{f}$ is a subanalytic subset of ${\accentset{\vee}{M}}\times{\accentset{\vee}{N}}$, and $q_{1}|_{{\overset{\mspace{4.0mu }\rule[-0.215pt]{6.88pt}{0.4945pt}}{\Gamma}}_{% \mspace{-3.0mu }f}}$ is proper. In particular, $f\colon{\mathsf{M}}\xrightarrow{}{\mathsf{N}}$ is a morphism of bordered spaces. (iii) ${\mathsf{M}}$ is smooth of dimension $d$ if $M$ is locally isomorphic to $\mathbb{R}^{d}$ as a subanalytic space. (iv) A subset $S$ of ${\mathsf{M}}$ (see Definition 2.3.6) is called subanalytic if it is subanalytic in ${\accentset{\vee}{M}}$. (v) A morphism $f\colon{\mathsf{M}}\xrightarrow{}{\mathsf{N}}$ of subanalytic bordered spaces is submersive if the continuous map ${\accentset{\circ}{f}}\colon{\accentset{\circ}{{\mathsf{M}}}}\xrightarrow{}{% \accentset{\circ}{{\mathsf{N}}}}$ is locally (in ${\accentset{\circ}{{\mathsf{M}}}}$) isomorphic to the projection ${\accentset{\circ}{{\mathsf{N}}}}\times\mathbb{R}^{d}\xrightarrow{}{\accentset% {\circ}{{\mathsf{N}}}}$ for some $d$.
