Definition 1.4.1. A triangulated functor $\Phi\colon\mathcal{S}\xrightarrow{}\mathcal{T}$ is called (i) left exact, if one has $\Phi(\mathcal{S}^{\geqslant c})\subset\mathcal{T}^{\geqslant c}$ for any $c\in\mathbb{R}$; (ii) right exact, if one has $\Phi(\mathcal{S}^{\leqslant c})\subset\mathcal{T}^{\leqslant c}$ for any $c\in\mathbb{R}$; (iii) exact, if it is both left and right exact.
Definition 3.3.4. (i) An $\mathrm{E}$-type on ${\mathsf{M}}$ is the datum $\mathcal{L}=(\varphi_{a},m_{a},\psi^{\pm}_{b},n_{b})_{a\in A,\ b\in B}$ consisting of (a) finite sets $A,B$, (b) integers $m_{a}$ and $n_{b}$ for any $a\in A$ and $b\in B$, (c) morphisms of subanalytic bordered spaces $\varphi_{a},\psi^{\pm}_{b}\colon{\mathsf{M}}\xrightarrow{}{\mathbb{R}_{\infty}}$ for any $a\in A$ and $b\in B$, such that $\psi^{-}_{b}(x)<\psi^{+}_{b}(x)$ for any $x\in{M}$. (ii) An $\mathrm{E}$-type $\mathcal{L}$ as in (3.3.1) is called stable if for any $b\in B$ $\overline{\{(x,t)\in{M}\times\mathbb{R}\nobreak\mskip 2.0mu \mathpunct{}% \nonscript\mskip-3.0mu {;}\mskip 6.0mu plus 1.0mu t=\psi^{+}_{b}(x)-\psi^{-}_{% b}(x)\}}\cap({\accentset{\vee}{M}}\times\{+\infty\})\neq\varnothing,$ where $\overline{\ast}$ denotes the closure in ${\accentset{\vee}{M}}\times{\overline{\mathbb{R}}}$.
Definition 2.6.1 ([4, Definition 4.6.3]). For $n\in\mathbb{Z}$, set $\displaystyle\mathrm{E}^{\leqslant n}({\mathsf{M}})$ $\displaystyle\mathbin{:=}\{K\in\mathrm{E}({\mathsf{M}})\nobreak\mskip 2.0mu % \mathpunct{}\nonscript\mskip-3.0mu {;}\mskip 6.0mu plus 1.0mu \operatorname{L^% {\mathrm{E}}}K\in\mathrm{D}^{\leqslant n}({\mathsf{M}}\times{\mathbb{R}_{% \infty}})\},$ $\displaystyle\mathrm{E}^{\geqslant n}({\mathsf{M}})$ $\displaystyle\mathbin{:=}\{K\in\mathrm{E}({\mathsf{M}})\nobreak\mskip 2.0mu % \mathpunct{}\nonscript\mskip-3.0mu {;}\mskip 6.0mu plus 1.0mu \operatorname{L^% {\mathrm{E}}}K\in\mathrm{D}^{\geqslant n}({\mathsf{M}}\times{\mathbb{R}_{% \infty}})\}.$
Definition 3.5.1. For $c\in\mathbb{R}$, consider the strictly full subcategories of $\mathrm{E}_{\mathbb{R}\text{-}\mathrm{c}}({\mathsf{M}})$ given by $\displaystyle\tensor*[^{p}]{\mathrm{E}}{{}_{\mathbb{R}\text{-}\mathrm{c}}^{% \leqslant c}}({\mathsf{M}})$ $\displaystyle\mathbin{:=}\tensor*[_{p}]{\mathrm{E}}{{}_{\mathbb{R}\text{-}% \mathrm{c}}^{\leqslant c}}({\mathsf{M}})\cap\tensor*[^{\prime}_{p}]{\mathrm{E}% }{{}_{\mathbb{R}\text{-}\mathrm{c}}^{\leqslant c+1/2}}({\mathsf{M}})$ $\displaystyle=\{K\in\mathrm{E}_{\mathbb{R}\text{-}\mathrm{c}}({\mathsf{M}})% \nobreak\mskip 2.0mu \mathpunct{}\nonscript\mskip-3.0mu {;}\mskip 6.0mu plus 1% .0mu K\in\tensor*[_{p}]{\mathrm{E}}{{}_{\mathbb{R}\text{-}\mathrm{c}}^{% \leqslant c}}({\mathsf{M}}),\ \mathrm{D}^{\mathrm{E}}_{\mathsf{M}}K\in\tensor*% [_{p^{*}}]{\mathrm{E}}{{}_{\mathbb{R}\text{-}\mathrm{c}}^{\geqslant-c-1/2}}({% \mathsf{M}})\},$ $\displaystyle\tensor*[^{p}]{\mathrm{E}}{{}_{\mathbb{R}\text{-}\mathrm{c}}^{% \geqslant c}}({\mathsf{M}})$ $\displaystyle\mathbin{:=}\tensor*[_{p}]{\mathrm{E}}{{}_{\mathbb{R}\text{-}% \mathrm{c}}^{\geqslant c-1/2}}({\mathsf{M}})\cap\tensor*[^{\prime}_{p}]{% \mathrm{E}}{{}_{\mathbb{R}\text{-}\mathrm{c}}^{\geqslant c}}({\mathsf{M}})$ $\displaystyle=\{K\in\mathrm{E}_{\mathbb{R}\text{-}\mathrm{c}}({\mathsf{M}})% \nobreak\mskip 2.0mu \mathpunct{}\nonscript\mskip-3.0mu {;}\mskip 6.0mu plus 1% .0mu \mathrm{D}^{\mathrm{E}}_{\mathsf{M}}K\in\tensor*[^{p}]{\mathrm{E}}{{}_{% \mathbb{R}\text{-}\mathrm{c}}^{\leqslant-c}}({\mathsf{M}})\}$ $\displaystyle=\{K\in\mathrm{E}_{\mathbb{R}\text{-}\mathrm{c}}({\mathsf{M}})% \nobreak\mskip 2.0mu \mathpunct{}\nonscript\mskip-3.0mu {;}\mskip 6.0mu plus 1% .0mu K\in\tensor*[_{p}]{\mathrm{E}}{{}_{\mathbb{R}\text{-}\mathrm{c}}^{% \geqslant c-1/2}}({\mathsf{M}}),\ \mathrm{D}^{\mathrm{E}}_{\mathsf{M}}K\in% \tensor*[_{p^{*}}]{\mathrm{E}}{{}_{\mathbb{R}\text{-}\mathrm{c}}^{\leqslant-c}% }({\mathsf{M}})\}.$
Definition 6.7. The simplicial amalgams over ${\bf X}$ in ${\bf C}$ and homomorphisms of such amalgams form the objects and morphisms of a category that we shall denote $\mathop{\rm\bf Amal}\nolimits_{\bf X}({\bf C})$. It is a subcategory of the functor quasi-category $[{\bf X},{\bf C}]$, which itself is (isomorphic to) a category since ${\bf X}$ is a small category (see [AdaHerStr90]).
Definition 3.9. The zero cohomology set is $H^{0}(X,{\mathcal{A}})=Z^{0}(X,{\mathcal{A}})$. The orbits in $Z^{1}(X,{\mathcal{A}})$ under the action defined above are called $1$-cohomology classes. The first cohomology set is the collection of ${\mathcal{C}}_{0}$ orbits of $1$-cocycles. We write $H^{1}(X,{\mathcal{A}})=Z^{1}(X,{\mathcal{A}})^{{\mathcal{C}}^{0}}.$ Moreover, for each $z\in Z^{i}(X,{\mathcal{A}})$ we denote its cohomology class as $[z]$. Note that for $z\in Z^{0}(X,{\mathcal{A}})$ we have $[z]=\{z\}$.
Definition 2.4. Adopting the notation from Definition 2.3, suppose $\tilde{X}=(\tilde{V},\tilde{\Sigma})$ is a simplicial complex such that $V\subseteq\tilde{V}$ and $\Sigma\subseteq\tilde{\Sigma}$. Given a simplicial amalgam $({\mathcal{G}}_{\bullet},\varphi_{\bullet}^{\bullet})$ over $X$, we define a simplicial amalgam $(\tilde{{\mathcal{G}}},\tilde{\varphi}_{\bullet}^{\bullet})$ over $\tilde{X}$ as follows. $\begin{array}[]{lcl}\tilde{G}_{\sigma}=\left\{\begin{array}[]{ll}G_{\sigma}&% \mbox{ if }\sigma\in\Sigma\\ \{1\}&\mbox{ else }\end{array}\right.&\mbox{ and }\tilde{\varphi}_{\tau}^{% \sigma}=\left\{\begin{array}[]{ll}\varphi_{\tau}^{\sigma}&\mbox{ if }\sigma,% \tau\in\Sigma\\ \tilde{G}_{\tau}=\{1\}\hookrightarrow\tilde{G}_{\sigma}&\mbox{ else. }\end{% array}\right.\end{array}$ Now if $\phi=\{\phi_{\sigma}\mid\sigma\in\Sigma\}\colon{\mathcal{G}}^{(1)}\to{\mathcal% {G}}^{(2)}$ is a homomorphism, then we define $\tilde{\phi}=\{\tilde{\phi}_{\sigma}\mid\sigma\in\tilde{\Sigma}\}\colon\tilde{% {\mathcal{G}}}^{(1)}\to\tilde{{\mathcal{G}}}^{(2)}$ as follows. $\tilde{\phi}_{\sigma}=\left\{\begin{array}[]{ll}\phi_{\sigma}&\mbox{ if }% \sigma\in\Sigma\\ \mathop{\rm id}\nolimits\colon\tilde{G}_{\sigma}^{(1)}=\{1\}\to\{1\}=\tilde{G}% _{\sigma}^{(2)}&\mbox{ else. }\end{array}\right.$
Definition 6.2. A morphism $A\stackrel{{\scriptstyle f}}{{\to}}B$ is called an embedding if (1) the underlying function $|A|\stackrel{{\scriptstyle f}}{{\to}}|B|$ is injective, and (2) $f$ is initial, i.e. for any $C\in\mathop{\rm obj}\nolimits({\bf C})$, a function $|C|\stackrel{{\scriptstyle g}}{{\to}}|A|$ underlies a ${\bf C}$-morphism whenever $|C|\stackrel{{\scriptstyle f\circ g}}{{\to}}|B|$ underlies a ${\bf C}$-morphism.
Definition 3.2. We define a homomorphism between coefficient systems ${\mathcal{A}}^{(2)}=\{A_{\bullet}^{(2)},{}^{(2)}\alpha_{\bullet}^{\bullet}\}$ and ${\mathcal{A}}^{(1)}=\{A_{\bullet}^{(1)},{}^{(1)}\alpha_{\bullet}^{\bullet}\}$ to be a map $\chi=\{\chi_{\sigma}\mid\sigma\in\Sigma\}$ where $\chi_{\sigma}\colon A_{\sigma}^{(2)}\to A^{(1)}_{\sigma}$ are group homomorphisms such that $\chi_{\tau}\mathbin{\circ}{}^{(2)}\alpha^{\sigma}_{\tau}={}^{(1)}\alpha^{% \sigma}_{\tau}\mathbin{\circ}\chi_{\sigma}.$ We call $\chi$ an isomorphism of coefficient systems if $\chi_{\sigma}$ is bijective for all $\sigma\in\Sigma$.
Definition 6.5. For an amalgam ${\mathcal{G}}$ and each $\sigma,\tau\in\Sigma$ with $\sigma\leq\tau$ we define $|\overline{\mathcal{G}}_{\sigma,\tau}|=\phi^{\sigma}_{\tau}(|{\mathcal{G}}_{% \tau}|)\subseteq|{\mathcal{G}}_{\sigma}|.$ Note that this is a set, not an object of ${\bf C}$. Given an amalgam ${}^{0}{\mathcal{G}}$, an amalgam of type ${}^{0}{\mathcal{G}}$ is an amalgam ${\mathcal{G}}$ such that ${\mathcal{G}}_{\sigma}={}^{0}{\mathcal{G}}_{\sigma}$ for all $\sigma\in\Sigma$ and $|\overline{{}^{0}{\mathcal{G}}}_{\sigma,\tau}|=|\overline{{\mathcal{G}}}_{% \sigma,\tau}|$ for all $\sigma,\tau\in\Sigma$ with $\sigma\leq\tau$. We call ${\mathcal{G}}$ normalized if for any simplex $\tau$ we have ${\mathcal{G}}("{\overline{\tau}}\leq\tau")=^{0}\!{\mathcal{G}}("{\overline{% \tau}}\leq\tau")$.
Definition 3.6. For $i=0,1$, the set of $i$-cocycles of ${\mathcal{C}}$ is $Z^{i}(X,{\mathcal{A}})=\{z\in{\mathcal{C}}^{i}\mid d_{i}(z)=\mathop{\rm id}% \nolimits_{i+1}\}$.
Definition 6.8. The coefficient system associated to the amalgam ${\mathcal{G}}=\{{\mathcal{G}}_{\bullet},\psi_{\bullet}^{\bullet}\}$ is the (covariant) functor ${\mathcal{A}}\colon{\bf X}\to\mathop{\rm\bf Group}\nolimits$, where for each simplex $\sigma\in\Sigma=\mathop{\rm obj}\nolimits({\bf X})$ we have ${\mathcal{A}}(\sigma)=\{g\in\mathop{\rm Aut}\nolimits_{\bf C}({\mathcal{G}}_{% \sigma})\mid g(|\overline{\mathcal{G}}_{\sigma,\tau}|)=|\overline{\mathcal{G}}% _{\sigma,\tau}|\mbox{ for all }\tau\mbox{ with }\sigma\leq\tau\},$ and for every $\sigma,\tau\in\Sigma$ with $\sigma\leq\tau$ we have $\begin{array}[]{rl}{\mathcal{A}}("\sigma\leq\tau")\colon A_{\sigma}&\to A_{% \tau}\\ f&\mapsto(\psi^{\sigma}_{\tau})^{-1}\circ f\circ\psi^{\sigma}_{\tau}.\\ \end{array}$ As before we shall write ${\mathcal{A}}=\{A_{\bullet},\alpha_{\bullet}^{\bullet}\}$, where $A_{\sigma}={\mathcal{A}}(\sigma)$ and $\alpha^{\sigma}_{\tau}={\mathcal{A}}("\sigma\leq\tau")$.
Definition 2.2. A simplicial amalgam over the complex $X=(V,\Sigma)$ is a collection ${\mathcal{G}}=\{G_{\sigma},\varphi^{\sigma}_{\tau}\mid\sigma\subseteq\tau,% \sigma,\tau\in\Sigma\}$, where each $G_{\sigma}$ is a group and, for each pair $(\sigma,\tau)$ such that $\sigma\subseteq\tau$ we have a monomorphism $\varphi^{\sigma}_{\tau}\colon G_{\tau}\hookrightarrow G_{\sigma}$, called an inclusion map such that, whenever $\sigma\subseteq\rho\subseteq\tau$, we have $\varphi^{\sigma}_{\rho}\mathbin{\circ}\varphi^{\rho}_{\tau}=\varphi^{\sigma}_{\tau}$. For simplicity we shall write $\overline{G}_{\sigma,\tau}=\varphi^{\sigma}_{\tau}(G_{\tau})\leq G_{\sigma}$. We shall use the shorthand notation ${\mathcal{G}}=\{G_{\bullet},\varphi_{\bullet}^{\bullet}\}$. A completion of ${\mathcal{G}}$ is a group $G$ together with a collection $\phi=\{\phi_{\sigma}\mid\sigma\in\Sigma\}$ of homomorphisms $\phi_{\sigma}\colon G_{\sigma}\to G$, such that whenever $\sigma\subseteq\tau$, we have $\phi_{\sigma}\mathbin{\circ}\varphi^{\sigma}_{\tau}=\phi_{\tau}$. The amalgam ${\mathcal{G}}$ is non-collapsing if it has a non-trivial completion. A completion $(\widehat{G},\widehat{\phi})$ is called universal if for any completion $(G,\phi)$ there is a (necessarily unique) surjective group homomorphism $\pi\colon\widehat{G}\to G$ such that $\phi=\pi\mathbin{\circ}\widehat{\phi}$.
Definition 2.7. We call an amalgam ${\mathcal{G}}=\{G_{\sigma},\varphi^{\sigma}_{\tau}\}$ of type ${\mathcal{G}}_{0}$ normalized if for any simplex $\tau$ we have $\varphi^{\overline{\tau}}_{\tau}=\psi^{\overline{\tau}}_{\tau}$, where $\overline{\tau}$ is the least maximal face in $\partial\tau$.
Definition 3.11. A normal subsystem of ${\mathcal{A}}$ is a collection $\{N_{\sigma}\mid\sigma\in\Sigma\}$ of normal subgroups $N_{\sigma}\lhd A_{\sigma}$ such that ${\mathcal{N}}=\{N_{\bullet},\alpha_{\bullet}^{\bullet}\}$ is a coefficient system on $X$. We shall denote this as ${\mathcal{N}}\lhd{\mathcal{A}}$. The normal sub coefficient system naturally gives rise to a quotient coefficient system by setting ${\mathcal{A}}/{\mathcal{N}}=\{A_{\bullet}/N_{\bullet},\alpha_{\bullet}^{% \bullet}\}$. Note that for $i=0,1$, ${\mathcal{C}}^{i}({\mathcal{N}})\lhd{\mathcal{C}}^{i}({\mathcal{A}})$ and therefore, ${\mathcal{C}}^{i}({\mathcal{A}}/{\mathcal{N}})\cong{\mathcal{C}}^{i}({\mathcal% {A}})/{\mathcal{C}}^{i}({\mathcal{N}})$.
Definition 2.3. We define a homomorphism between the amalgams ${\mathcal{G}}^{(1)}=\{G_{\bullet}^{(1)},{}^{(1)}\varphi_{\bullet}^{\bullet}\}$ and ${\mathcal{G}}^{(2)}=\{G_{\bullet}^{(2)},{}^{(2)}\varphi_{\bullet}^{\bullet}\}$ to be a map $\phi=\{\phi_{\sigma}\mid\sigma\in\Sigma\}$ where $\phi_{\sigma}\colon G_{\sigma}^{(1)}\to G^{(2)}_{\sigma}$ are group homomorphisms such that $\phi_{\sigma}\mathbin{\circ}{}^{(1)}\varphi^{\sigma}_{\tau}={}^{(2)}\varphi^{% \sigma}_{\tau}\mathbin{\circ}\phi_{\tau}.$ We call $\phi$ an isomorphism of amalgams if $\phi_{\sigma}$ is bijective for all $\sigma\in\Sigma$.
Definition 3.3. Adopting the notation from Definition 3.2, suppose $\tilde{X}=(\tilde{V},\tilde{\Sigma})$ is a simplicial complex such that $V\subseteq\tilde{V}$ and $\Sigma\subseteq\tilde{\Sigma}$. Given a coefficient system $({\mathcal{A}}_{\bullet},\alpha_{\bullet}^{\bullet})$ over $X$, we define a coefficient system $(\tilde{{\mathcal{A}}},\tilde{\alpha}_{\bullet}^{\bullet})$ over $\tilde{X}$ as follows. $\begin{array}[]{lcl}\tilde{A}_{\sigma}=\left\{\begin{array}[]{ll}A_{\sigma}&% \mbox{ if }\sigma\in\Sigma\\ \{1\}&\mbox{ else }\end{array}\right.&\mbox{ and }\tilde{\alpha}_{\tau}^{% \sigma}=\left\{\begin{array}[]{ll}\alpha_{\tau}^{\sigma}&\mbox{ if }\sigma,% \tau\in\Sigma\\ \tilde{A}_{\sigma}\to\tilde{A}_{\tau}=\{1\}&\mbox{ else. }\end{array}\right.% \end{array}$ Now if $\phi=\{\phi_{\sigma}\mid\sigma\in\Sigma\}\colon{\mathcal{A}}^{(2)}\to{\mathcal% {A}}^{(1)}$ is a homomorphism, then we define $\tilde{\phi}=\{\tilde{\phi}_{\sigma}\mid\sigma\in\tilde{\Sigma}\}\colon\tilde{% {\mathcal{A}}}^{(2)}\to\tilde{{\mathcal{A}}}^{(1)}$ as follows. $\tilde{\phi}_{\sigma}=\left\{\begin{array}[]{ll}\phi_{\sigma}&\mbox{ if }% \sigma\in\Sigma\\ \mathop{\rm id}\nolimits\colon\tilde{A}_{\sigma}^{(2)}=\{1\}\to\{1\}=\tilde{A}% _{\sigma}^{(1)}&\mbox{ else. }\end{array}\right.$
Definition 2.6. Let ${\mathcal{G}}_{0}=\{G_{\bullet},\psi_{\bullet}^{\bullet}\}$ be an amalgam over $X=(V,\Sigma)$. An amalgam of type ${\mathcal{G}}_{0}$ is an amalgam ${\mathcal{G}}=\{G_{\bullet},\varphi_{\bullet}^{\bullet}\}$, where, for each $\sigma\in\Sigma$, the group $G_{\sigma}$ is that of ${\mathcal{G}}_{0}$ and in which $\varphi^{\sigma}_{\tau}(G_{\sigma})=\overline{G}_{\sigma,\tau}=\psi^{\sigma}_{% \tau}(G_{\sigma})$ for each pair $(\sigma,\tau)$ with $\sigma\subseteq\tau\in\Sigma$.
Definition 6.4. A simplicial amalgam over ${\bf X}$ in the (concrete) category ${\bf C}$ is a contravariant functor ${\mathcal{G}}:{\bf X}\to{\bf C}$ such that for any pair of simplices $\sigma,\tau$ with $\sigma\leq\tau$, the map ${\mathcal{G}}("\sigma\leq\tau")\colon{\mathcal{G}}(\tau)\to{\mathcal{G}}(\sigma)$ is an embedding (so in particular ${\mathcal{G}}("\sigma\leq\tau")$ is a monomorphism). By analogy with the group theoretic setting we shall denote ${\mathcal{G}}(\sigma)$ by ${\mathcal{G}}_{\sigma}$ and ${\mathcal{G}}("\sigma\leq\tau")$ by $\varphi^{\sigma}_{\tau}$ and write ${\mathcal{G}}=({\mathcal{G}}_{\bullet},\varphi^{\bullet}_{\bullet})$.
Definition 3.1. A coefficient system on the simplicial complex $X=(V,\Sigma)$ is a collection ${\mathcal{A}}=\{A_{\sigma},\alpha^{\sigma}_{\tau}\mid\sigma\subseteq\tau\mbox{% with }\sigma,\tau\in\Sigma\},$ where $A_{\sigma}$ is a group and $\alpha^{\sigma}_{\tau}\colon A_{\sigma}\to A_{\tau}$ is a group homomorphism such that whenever $\sigma\subseteq\rho\subseteq\tau$, we have $\alpha^{\sigma}_{\tau}=\alpha^{\rho}_{\tau}\mathbin{\circ}\alpha^{\sigma}_{\rho}$. As for amalgams, we shall use the shorthand notation ${\mathcal{A}}=\{A_{\bullet},\alpha_{\bullet}^{\bullet}\}$.
Definition 6.1. A concrete category (over ${\mathop{\rm\bf Set}\nolimits}$) is a category ${\bf C}$ equiped with a functor $F:{\bf C}\to{\mathop{\rm\bf Set}\nolimits}$ that is faithful, that is, for objects $A,B\in\mathop{\rm obj}\nolimits({\bf C})$, the hom-set restrictions $F\colon\hom_{\bf C}(A,B)\to\hom_{\mathop{\rm\bf Set}\nolimits}(FA,FB)$ are injective. The functor $F$ is called the forgetful functor. In [AdaHerStr90] a concrete category over ${\mathop{\rm\bf Set}\nolimits}$ is called a construct.
Definition 6.10. A ($G$-equivariant) sheaf on $X(\Gamma)$ is a collection ${\mathcal{F}}_{\Gamma}=\{{\mathcal{F}}_{\sigma},\phi^{\sigma}_{\tau}\mid\sigma% \subseteq\tau\in\Sigma(\Gamma)\},$ where ${\mathcal{F}}_{\sigma}$ is a $k$-vector space and $\phi^{\sigma}_{\tau}\colon{\mathcal{F}}_{\tau}\to{\mathcal{F}}_{\sigma}$ is a linear map whenever $\sigma\subseteq\tau\in\Sigma$. Moreover, $\phi^{\sigma}_{\rho}\mathbin{\circ}\phi^{\rho}_{\tau}=\phi^{\sigma}_{\tau}$ whenever $\sigma\leq\rho\leq\tau$. Finally we require that $G$ acts on the set $\prod_{\sigma}{\mathcal{F}}_{\sigma}$. More precisely, $g\in G$ acts linearly via $\tilde{g}_{\sigma}:{\mathcal{F}}_{\sigma}\to{\mathcal{F}}_{\sigma g}$ and the following diagram commutes.
Definition 6.6. We define a homomorphism between the amalgams ${\mathcal{G}}^{(1)}=\{{\mathcal{G}}_{\bullet}^{(1)},{}^{(1)}\varphi_{\bullet}^% {\bullet}\}$ and ${\mathcal{G}}^{(2)}=\{{\mathcal{G}}_{\bullet}^{(2)},{}^{(2)}\varphi_{\bullet}^% {\bullet}\}$ to be a natural transformation $\phi\colon{\mathcal{G}}^{(1)}\to{\mathcal{G}}^{(2)}$. That is, $\phi=\{\phi_{\sigma}\mid\sigma\in\Sigma\}$ where $\phi_{\sigma}\in\hom_{\bf C}({\mathcal{G}}_{\sigma}^{(1)},{\mathcal{G}}^{(2)}_% {\sigma})$ is such that, when $\sigma\leq\tau$ we have $\xymatrix{{\mathcal{G}}^{(1)}_{\sigma}\ar[r]^{\phi_{\sigma}}&{\mathcal{G}}^{(2% )}_{\sigma}\\ {\mathcal{G}}^{(1)}_{\tau}\ar[u]^{{}^{(1)}\varphi^{\sigma}_{\tau}}\ar[r]^{\phi% _{\tau}}&{\mathcal{G}}^{(2)}_{\tau}\ar[u]_{{}^{(2)}\varphi^{\sigma}_{\tau}}\\ }$ We call $\phi$ an isomorphism of amalgams if it is a natural isomorphism, that is, if $\phi_{\sigma}$ is an isomorphism for all $\sigma\in\Sigma$.
